member.remarks:
            Legend:

              #n - integer identifier of task;

              ^n - hash code of cancellation token/source;

              $n - managed thread identifier;

            The supposed usage is in view models:

            * view model creates task group and schedules all its tasks in this group;

            * when view model is activated then appropriate group brings to foreground;

            * as result - tasks related to vm which user looks over are executed first.

member.summary:
            Implements parallel sort:

              split source list onto fragments according to parallezim degree;
              sort them concurrently; then perform eighter single k-way merge or parallel 2-way merges.

member.remarks:
            The following sorts are supported

             * out-place QuickSort with optional sub-range;

             * in-place QuickSort with optional sub-range;

             * out-place StableSort with optional sub-range;

             * in-place StableSort with optional sub-range.



            Requires approx. 2 * n * sizeof(T) of additional memory.



            All internal allocations are LOH-free.

member.summary:
            Implements parallel transform:

              split source list onto fragments according to parallezim degree;
              transform them concurrently; then concatenates them into single enumerable.

members.member:
/// 
Specifies task succeeded callback restricted by .


See generic OnXxx() remarks on .
        
@this

member.example:
var result = controller
  .Fork(DoA, inputA, DoB, inputB)
  .Join(DoC);

example.code:
using (controller.StartProgress(100))
{
  for (var i = 0; i < 100; i++)
  {
    // do something useful
    controller.YieldAndAdvanceProgress();
  }
}

using (controller.StartProgress(2))
{
  var subTaskA = controller.Fork(DoAsyncOpA);
  var subTaskB = controller.Fork(DoAsyncOpB);

  controller
    .AttachSubOperation(subTaskA, 1)
    .AttachSubOperation(subTaskB, 1)
    .Wait(taskA, timeout)
    .Wait(taskB, timeout);
}

using (controller.Lock(myMutex, Waitable.InfiniteTimeout))
{
  // do something under lock
}

member.remarks:
            Calls StartProgress(100) on provided execution controller.

            Usage pattern:
            
            using (controller.AsJetProgress(out var progress))
            {
              progress.Begin(count);
              for (...)
              {
                ...
                progress.YieldAndAdvance();
              }
            }

            Calls CreateSubOperation(parentSteps).StartProgress(100) on provided execution controller.

            Usage pattern:
            
            using (controller.AsJetProgress(out var progress))
            {
              progress.Begin(count);
              for (...)
              {
                ...
                progress.YieldAndAdvance();
              }
            }

member.summary:
            The simplest implementation of  which:

              * can not be cancelled;

              * just ignore progress reporting;

              * has non cancellable wait;

              * execute fork action instantly and return completed task.

member.param:
Flag indicating whether percent display will be aligned to the left or to the right. Difference is in display precision for values between 1 and 10%: 
            if percents are aligned to the left, we try to preserve display width, so values will have 2 digits after separator (total width = 3 digits + 1 separator for any percent value), 
            otherwise we try to preserve decimal separator position, so these values will have 1 digit after separator, as well as values >= 10 %
